  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "Legal precedents related to money laundering cases vary by jurisdiction, but several key cases and principles have shaped the legal landscape globally. Below are some notable examples and principles from major jurisdictions:\n\n### United States\n1. **United States v. Bajakajian (1998)**  \n   - **Issue:** Whether the forfeiture of currency exceeding $357,000 for failure to report it when leaving the country violated the Excessive Fines Clause of the Eighth Amendment.  \n   - **Precedent:** The Supreme Court ruled that the forfeiture was grossly disproportionate to the offense and violated the Excessive Fines Clause. This case set limits on asset forfeiture in money laundering cases.\n\n2. **United States v. Santos (2008)**  \n   - **Issue:** Whether the term \"proceeds\" in the federal money laundering statute refers to gross receipts or only to profits.  \n   - **Precedent:** The Supreme Court held that \"proceeds\" means profits, not gross receipts, in cases where interpreting it as gross receipts would lead to a merger problem with other crimes.\n\n3. **United States v. Regalado Cuellar (2008)**  \n   - **Issue:** Whether the government must prove that the defendant knew the specific purpose of the money laundering transaction.  \n   - **Precedent:** The Supreme Court ruled that the government must prove the defendant intended to conceal the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of the proceeds, not just the movement of money.\n\n### United Kingdom\n1. **R v. Montila (2004)**  \n   - **Issue:** The interpretation of \"criminal property\" under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002.  \n   - **Precedent:** The House of Lords clarified that for property to be considered \"criminal property,\" it must be proven to have been obtained through criminal conduct.\n\n2. **Director of the Serious Fraud Office v. Lexi Holdings (2008)**  \n   - **Issue:** Whether a director of a company could be liable for money laundering under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002.  \n   - **Precedent:** The court held that directors could be personally liable if they were involved in or facilitated money laundering activities.\n\n### European Union\n1. **Case C-617/10, \u00c5kerberg Fransson (2013)**  \n   - **Issue:** The application of EU Charter of Fundamental Rights in national proceedings related to money laundering.  \n   - **Precedent:** The European Court of Justice ruled that fundamental rights under the EU Charter must be respected in national proceedings when implementing EU law, including anti-money laundering regulations.\n\n2. **Case C-537/16, Garlsson Real Estate (2018)**  \n   - **Issue:** The interpretation of the EU Money Laundering Directive regarding the scope of obliged entities.  \n   - **Precedent:** The court clarified that entities involved in real estate transactions must comply with anti-money laundering obligations, reinforcing the broad scope of the directive.\n\n### International\n1. **FATF Recommendations**  \n   - The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets international standards for combating money laundering. While not a legal precedent per se, FATF recommendations often influence national legislation and judicial interpretations globally.\n\n2. **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**  \n   - This treaty has been instrumental in shaping national laws against money laundering, particularly in relation to drug trafficking.\n\n### Common Principles\n- **Knowledge or Intent:** Courts generally require proof that the defendant knew or intended to launder money derived from criminal activity.\n- **Concealment:** Transactions must typically involve an element of concealment or disguise to constitute money laundering.\n- **Proportionality:** Asset forfeiture and penalties must be proportionate to the offense.\n\nThese precedents and principles guide the interpretation and enforcement of anti-money laundering laws worldwide, but specific outcomes can vary based on local statutes and judicial interpretations.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
